org.safs.model.tools

Class EmbeddedHookDriverRunner

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.safs.model.tools.EmbeddedHookDriverRunner
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    JSAFSConfiguredClassStore

    public class EmbeddedHookDriverRunner
extends java.lang.Object
implements JSAFSConfiguredClassStore
    This Runner is an access point to a minimalist EmbeddedHookDriver Driver API. See the EmbeddedHookDriver reference for a list of known available subclasses.
    Author:
    Carl Nagle
    See Also:
    EmbeddedHookDriver

      • getConfiguredClassInstance

        public java.lang.Object getConfiguredClassInstance(java.lang.String classname)
        When using JSAFS to automatically instantiate, configure, and execute tests across many classes and packages the user can retrieve those otherwise unavailable class object instances here. This can be useful if the class instance will capture test execution information or data that you want to examine.
        Specified by:
        getConfiguredClassInstance in interface JSAFSConfiguredClassStore
        Parameters:
        classname - -- the full package name of the class to retrieve. ex: my.test.package.MyTest
        Returns:
        the object instance that was instantiated and used, or null if we have no instance of the specified class.

      • run

        public void run()
        Initiates the embedded drivers and engine to start running if it is not already running. The user should call either this method or the autorun to ensure the drivers are initialized before trying to use them.
        See Also:
        autorun(String[])

      • autorun

        public void autorun(java.lang.String[] args)
             throws java.lang.Throwable
        This is the critical method users could call to commence the automatic instantiation, configuration, and execution of JSAFSTest methods.

        Minimalist example: 

               public static void main(String[] args)throws Throwable{
         MyTestApp app = new MyTestApp();
         
         new Runner().autorun(args);
         ...
     }

        Automatic configuration and usage is not required. The user can control test configuration and execution within their custom code if they want.

        Parameters:
        args - passed in from command-line Java-- the primordial main(String[] args)
        Usually, it is the class who calls Runner.autorun() will be considered as
        the class that is requesting the automatic configuration and execution, but we can also
        change it by providing parameter as "-autorunclass autorun.full.classname".
        Throws:
        java.lang.Throwable
        See Also:
        JSAFSTest
